First of all when we first arrived, they sat us in the back in a space with absolutely no lighting so we requested a seat change. Anyways. service was extremely slow; our main waiter didn’t even speak English. I had to ask for the same thing 4 times and he looked so confused and finally asked another waiter to translate after the 4th time. The shumai appetizer was nasty and did not taste like traditional shumai . It was also cold and undercooked so we sent it back and switched the order to calamari. The calamari was better but still nothing special and nothing comparable to calamari I’ve had at other Thai places. The pork chop was good—not great. It was a bit over cooked. However, the sautéed veggies were tasty and I liked my drink. I asked if I could substitute the veggies or white rice for fried rice and they just laughed and said no—-I don’t think it was a big deal or some crazy request but I guess they don’t know how to please paying customers. Overall food was just alright—nothing to return to, and not authentic—just something quick and not too expensive to eat. Employees were nice but service was way too slow and incompetent and it wasn’t even crowded. The best thing is probably the drinks. I won’t be returning. I wish I could get a refund honestly—but my friend and I were just so exhausted and hungry from a long days of work so we just decided to stay there and finish the food. The food even made him feel a little sick —please be weary and don’t be fooled by all the good reviews—that’s how I got tricked and lured in, in the first place. IG: @threetravelingtongues

I visited Lantern for lunch yesterday and I am so disgusted with the service I received. As we entered we let the hostess know we needed an order to go, after I looked at the menu I told the cashier what I wanted to order and as I’m waiting for my colleague to decide, the cashier blurts out “what you want?” A little appalled, he asked her to wait politely until he had a chance to take a good look at the menu. We then ordered and paid and waited for our order at the bar. While waiting, I watched several people come in and pick up their orders very pleasantly and when it was our turn, she came over and dropped our order on the counter while walking away saying thank you. My colleague honestly wanted to speak to the manager but I told him it wasn’t worth it, we would just never eat from there again. Turns out, I will definitely never eat from there again since I got a horrible case of diarrhea. Stay away from this place. Horrible service and even worst food!

Lantern is a consistent, simple neighborhood Thai restaurant in Brooklyn Heights.  Pros: Reasonable prices, prompt service, delivery options. Also, not many other Thai restaurants in the neighborhood (the other one has better food but has horrible NYC sanitation scores, making it a non-option). Great outdoor seating, as well.  Cons: The food here is especially bland and the menu is very mainstream.  Summary: Its a safe option in a neighborhood without many Thai options. If you're looking for a safe bet or quick delivery, this is your place. If you want a special Thai experience - you may want to look elsewhere.

We were looking for a simple lunch so we ordered crab rangoons, virgin rolls and pineapple rice. The rangoons were probably the best I've ever had (we got a second order of these two!). Light and crispy pouches with the perfect blend of crab and cream cheese with a yummy honey-chili sauce. Virgin rolls were fresh with baby spinach, celery, alfalfa sprouts, tofu and avocado, served with terrific dark brown honey -citrus sauce. The pineapple rice I ordered with shrimp and there was plenty, almost enough for two. Staff was attentive but not overbearing and we ate outside on a beautiful Spring day. Absolute home run! Will return again!

Half the lanterns seemed to not have candles in them. Um, the place is called Lantern, isn’t it? This was our second time here, and it was not nearly as nice as the first time which was perhaps two years ago.
